				<div id="post-618" class="hentry p1 post publish author-canuckaholic category-hci category-interactivity-theory category-user-centered-design category-user-experience-design-2 untagged is-excerpt auto-excerpt comments-closed pings-closed y2011 m06 d09 h05 slug-5-principles-of-user-centered-navigation"><h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://popdigital.ca/2011/06/09/5-principles-of-user-centered-navigation/" title="Permalink to 5 Principles of User-Centered Navigation" rel="bookmark">5 Principles of User-Centered Navigation</a></h2>
<div class="entry-meta"><span class="meta-prep meta-prep-author">By </span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://popdigital.ca/author/admin/" title="View all posts by Adrian">Adrian</a></span><span class="meta-sep meta-sep-entry-date"> | </span><span class="meta-prep meta-prep-entry-date">Published: </span><span class="entry-date"><abbr class="published" title="2011-06-09T12:44:49-0700">June 9, 2011</abbr></span></div><!-- .entry-meta -->
					<div class="entry-content">
<p>One of the most important concepts in navigation is that it should be easily learned. If it takes too long to grasp the navigational flow of a program, the user will become frustrated and lose interest. An easily learned navigation structure is the first step in creating user satisfaction. Instructions can be useful, but the [...]</p>
	
