				<div id="post-525" class="hentry p7 post publish author-canuckaholic category-interactivity-theory category-thoughts tag-game-design tag-game-theory tag-interactivity-theory-2 tag-non-linear-narrative tag-user-experience-design is-excerpt auto-excerpt comments-closed pings-closed y2011 m05 d08 h06 slug-story-vs-game"><h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://popdigital.ca/2011/05/08/story-vs-game/" title="Permalink to Story vs Game" rel="bookmark">Story vs Game</a></h2>
<div class="entry-meta"><span class="meta-prep meta-prep-author">By </span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://popdigital.ca/author/admin/" title="View all posts by Adrian">Adrian</a></span><span class="meta-sep meta-sep-entry-date"> | </span><span class="meta-prep meta-prep-entry-date">Published: </span><span class="entry-date"><abbr class="published" title="2011-05-08T13:58:53-0700">May 8, 2011</abbr></span></div><!-- .entry-meta -->
					<div class="entry-content">
<p>“The pleasure people derive from games is not dependent on their ability to tell stories.” If you are interested in how narrative can fit into games &#8211; to enhance the user experience, spin a unique non-linear tale, etc &#8211; then an article worth reading is Where Stories End and Games Begin by Greg Costikyan (costik.com/gamnstry.html). [...]</p>
	
