				<div id="post-534" class="hentry p8 post publish author-canuckaholic category-interactivity-theory category-user-experience-design-2 tag-experience tag-interactivity tag-language is-excerpt auto-excerpt comments-closed pings-closed y2011 m05 d07 h07 alt slug-building-a-language-for-an-interactive-experience"><h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://popdigital.ca/2011/05/07/building-a-language-for-an-interactive-experience/" title="Permalink to Building a Language for an Interactive Experience" rel="bookmark">Building a Language for an Interactive Experience</a></h2>
<div class="entry-meta"><span class="meta-prep meta-prep-author">By </span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://popdigital.ca/author/admin/" title="View all posts by Adrian">Adrian</a></span><span class="meta-sep meta-sep-entry-date"> | </span><span class="meta-prep meta-prep-entry-date">Published: </span><span class="entry-date"><abbr class="published" title="2011-05-07T14:25:20-0700">May 7, 2011</abbr></span></div><!-- .entry-meta -->
					<div class="entry-content">
<p>ABSTRACT Interactive multimedia systems are often designed and implemented primarily through intuition, and thus a common language for creating an interactive experience is needed for the interactive system developer. This paper discusses building a language for an interactive experience by outlining the steps required, and principles involved in designing an interactive environment. A preliminary language [...]</p>
	
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->
